    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Option B: use our terms throughout for 仁义礼",
    "content": "B. Use our dictionary terms throughout, including in the block quote. Here is the key difference from 德: with 德 we made a genuinely unusual departure (\"character\" instead of \"virtue\"), so keeping \"virtue\" in the canonical quote prevents confusion. But \"humaneness\" for 仁, \"rightness\" for 义, and \"ritual conduct\" for 礼 are all well-established academic options — they are not unusual or idiosyncratic. A reader will recognize them immediately.\n\nSwitching terms between the block quote and the analysis for three separate concepts would create more confusion than it prevents. The reader would have to track that \"benevolence\" in the quote = \"humaneness\" in the analysis, \"righteousness\" = \"rightness\", \"rites\" = \"ritual conduct\" — that is three unnecessary equivalence mappings on top of the one we already have for 德. \n\nThe 德 split was justified because \"character\" is a genuine departure from tradition. For 仁/义/礼, our terms are close enough to standard usage that consistency serves the reader better than conformity to one particular canonical translation."
  }
}
